@Node "introduction" "NewLookMenuPatch/Introduction"

  When  I  had  an A1200 (sold it coz AGA is such a pig) I loved
the  black  on  white  NewLook  menus of Workbench 3.  I decided
recently  to  begin  programming a gui that would have NLM's but
soon  ran  into  bother  when  the AmigaKey and CheckMark images
refused  to  appear  in  the  correct  colours.  They would only
appear  in  the  old  black/grey  colours, Grr.  I was angry and
frustrated  (which  makes  a  change  from  my normal  moody and
depressed  state),  so  I  started  tracking  down the offending
images...   Once  I had found them (and intuitions references to
them) I was able to begin programming NewLookMenuPatch (NLMP).


This is how NewLookMenuPatch works..

  First   NLMP   attempts   to  find  the  AmigaKey  graphic  in
chipmemory.   If found, NLMP will get a pointer to the intuition
library  and  look  for  a reference to the chip address.  If it
finds  one  it  checks to see if it's part of an intuition image
structure  and  if so it patches the structure to point to a new
NewLook)   AmigaKey)  graphic.   NLMP  does  the  same  for  the
checkmark graphic.  If either search/replace fails (or any other
operation fails) then NLMP will exit, undoing all changes it has
made.

  Both  Searches take place in the first $10000 (130kb) bytes of
chipmem.  Some Amiga owners with no fast memory might experience
quite  a  delay and NLMP may not be able to find the graphics at
all.   If  you  can't live with the delay then that's either too
tough  for  you  or  you  should  consider  purchasing some fast
memory.

  Once  the  image  patches  are in place the program sets about
patching  some  library vectors.  The patched libraries, vectors
and their new/extended functions are...

gadtools.library - _LVOCreateMenusA

  When   this   function  gets  called,  NLMP  will  strip  (ala
_LVOFilterTagItems)  any  GTMN_FrontPen  (which tells gtlib what
colour  to print menutext in) tag from the supplied taglist.  It
will  then  append  the  original  taglist  to  it's own taglist
containing  the  new GTMN_FrontPen value and then return control
to the normal _LVOCreateMenusA function.

*

intuition.library - _LVOOpenScreenTagList

  This  patch works more or less the same as the gadtools patch.
The differences are that it will strip'n'append SA_DetailPen and
SA_BlockPen tags.

*

intuition.library - _LVOOpenScreen

  This  patch will overwrite the ns_DetailPen and ns_BlockPen in
the  newscreen  structure.  If ns_Type contains NS_EXTENDED then
the  extension  taglist will get the strip'n'append action as in
_LVOOpenScreenTagList.

*

intuition.library - _LVOOpenWindowTagList
intuition.library - _LVOOpenWindow

  Both  these  tags  work  the same as their screen counterparts
except they work with windows instead of screens :^)

*

intuition.library - _LVOOpenWorkBench

  This function calls the original.  If the WBScreen is returned
then  it's  sc_DetailPen  and sc_BlockPen get overwritten.  It's
some  strange  behaviour  that  the  WBScreen never get's opened
legally.   Then  _LVOSetWindowTitles  will  get  called  so  the
menubar get's redrawn in the correct colours.

*

intuition.library - _LVOSetMenuStrip

  When  this  function  gets  called  NLMP will walk through all
menu's,  items, and subitems and fix (for lack of a better word)
the  pens  for the item text or image in the case of a barlabel.
This  function  does  this because some bad programs like v34.11
AmigaGuide  library  has  some strange way of making it's menus.
After  the  pens have been corrected the modified menu is passed
onto the original _LVOSetMenuStrip function.


  Phew,  that  was  a lot to absorb but let's continue with some
things that you should note before you try NLMP.

0. NLMP is not for OS3+!! You already have NewLookMenus!!

1. NLMP  will  only  work   correctly  on a  4 colour workbench.
   Screens that have more colours make the complement drawing of
   menus and their items different.  Blame it on gfx library :^)

2. NLMP will affect ALL screens and ALL windows that get opened.

3. NLMP will force (or attempt to) ALL  screens and ALL  windows
   to use DetailPen of 1 (black) and BlockPen of 2 (white).

4. Because  of  3,  ALL  window  gadgets  that are  disabled get
   frosted  in  white.  I am currently looking into this strange
   behaviour.. but IMHO it looks quite nice.. :^)

5. Currently  NLMP  cannot  simulate  the   black  line  that is
   present  at  the  bottom  of  WB3 NewLook menus.  If I try to
   render  it onto a screens titlebar and a window is there it's
   the  window  that  gets  drawn  on.  Mabye I should try using
   layers  instead  of  just  drawing into the screens rastport.
   Any help would be appreciated here..

6. ALL  the  intuition  structures  that  NLMP  changes are  not
   copied.   That  means  the  original structures passed in are
   modified.   If  you can't handle my program doing nasty stuff
   to your own then tough luck buddy :^)


  Wow!   I  didn't think there would be so much doc to write for
such  a  small  program.   Hmm..  Well that's about all for now.
Time  to install it and see if it works or kills you beloved Ami
:^)

Enjoy,
      Cliff Earl.

@EndNode

